The Dodgers deserved the chance to humiliate a Cleveland baseball team that not only persists in identifying itself as the â€œIndians,â€ but also resurrected the laughably racist, red-faced mascot Chief Wahoo just in time for the playoffs. 
For those who havenâ€™t kept up with the baseball drama, hereâ€™s a summary: The Cleveland team drew the curtain on its regular-season minstrel show in the spring, having replaced Chief Wahoo on its caps with a vintage red â€œC.â€ It never officially retired the offending mascot, but Wahoo remained confined only to uniform sleeves throughout the regular season, leading reasonable people to believe that the team ownership had finally seen the light where other franchises such as the NFLâ€™s Washington Redskins remained defiantly in the dark, and was easing its fans into the post-â€œIndiansâ€ era. 
Or so we thought. Chief Wahoo reappeared when the Cleveland team began its impressive playoff run against the Boston Red Sox, and he hasnâ€™t left. He remained stitched on hats and held aloft by adoring Cleveland fans as the team convincingly defeated the Toronto Blue Jays, even surviving a legal attack by advocates of Canadaâ€™s indigenous peoples that threatened to forbid even so much as the use of the term â€œIndiansâ€ while the team was on Canadian soil. 
{snip} 
Itâ€™s tempting to look past all this and take pity on a city thatâ€™s had it as rough as Cleveland. The Cubsâ€™ championship drought has famously lasted for 107 baseball seasons, but the Cleveland team boasts a pitiable 67 years without a World Series title. Beyond sports, Clevelandâ€™s decline as an important American metropolis is arguably unmatched, having tumbled from a population peak of 900,000-plus in 1950 to less than 400,000 today. {snip} 
But Cleveland? Hey, I know some generous, wonderfully caring people from that part of Ohio, which makes wishing for their teamâ€™s brutal defeat personally difficult. But being on the right side of a moral dispute isnâ€™t supposed to be easy, especially when the team in question isnâ€™t the evil Washington Redskins and its infernal owner, Daniel Snyder. Clevelandâ€™s municipal misery doesnâ€™t excuse the disgraceful exalting of Chief Wahoo any more than white menâ€™s economic hardship makes Donald Trumpâ€™s popularity OK. 
